{"title_page": "Tualatin station", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox Station\n | name           = {{MAX infobox header|Tualatin|wesstn=y}}\n | type           = [[WES Commuter Rail]] station\n | image          = Tualatin station platform view, showing gauntlet track (2015).jpg\n | image_caption  = Tualatin station seen in 2015\n | address        = 18955 SW Boones Ferry Road [[Tualatin, Oregon]], U.S.\n | country        = \n | line           = [[Portland and Western Railroad]]\n | coordinates    = {{coord|45.383283|-122.764556|format=dms|type:railwaystation_region:US-OR|display=inline,title}}\n | other          = \n | structure      = At-grade\n | platform       = 1 [[side platform]]\n | tracks         = 1\n | bus_operators  = \n | bus_routes     = \n | connections    = {{rint|bus|1}} '''TriMet''': 76{{br}}{{rint|bus|1}} '''Tualatin Shuttle'''\n | preceding      =\n | parking        = 129 spaces\n | bicycle        = [[Bicycle locker|Locker]]s and [[Bicycle parking rack|rack]]s\n | baggage_check  =\n | passengers     =\n | pass_year      =\n | pass_percent   =\n | pass_system    =\n | opened         = February 2, 2009\n | closed         =\n | rebuilt        =\n | ADA            = yes\n | code           =\n | owned          = [[TriMet]]\n | zone           =\n | services       = {{s-rail|title=WES}}\n{{s-line|system=WES|line=main|previous=Wilsonville|next=Tigard Transit Center}}\n | mpassengers=\n}}\n\n'''Tualatin ''' is a [[train station]] in [[Tualatin, Oregon]], United States. It is situated next to Hedges Green Shopping Center on [[Oregon Route 141|Southwest Boones Ferry Road]] in downtown Tualatin. The station is the second of five northbound stops on [[TriMet]]'s [[WES Commuter Rail]] after [[Wilsonville station]] and before [[Tigard Transit Center]]. The commuter rail line, which opened for regular service in February 2009, links the cities of [[Beaverton, Oregon|Beaverton]], [[Tigard, Oregon|Tigard]], Tualatin, and [[Wilsonville, Oregon|Wilsonville]] in the western suburbs of the [[Portland metropolitan area]]. WES connects with [[MAX Light Rail]] at [[Beaverton Transit Center]].\n\nThe station was approved as part of the [[Washington County, Oregon|Washington County]] commuter rail project in 2004. Construction was expected to begin in July 2007 but was delayed after issues emerged with its location, specifically the amount of available parking. A compromise was reached and construction began in January 2008. WES trains serve Tualatin station every thirty minutes on weekdays during the morning and evening [[rush hour]]s. Connections include TriMet bus route 76\u2013Hall/Greenburg and the [[Tualatin Shuttle]]. Tualatin station includes a 129-space [[park and ride]] lot.\n\n==History==\nBeginning in 1908, the [[Oregon Electric Railway]] (OE), which operated an [[interurban]] line between [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]] and [[Salem, Oregon|Salem]], served the community of Tualatin. At its peak, the line extended south as far as [[Eugene, Oregon|Eugene]].<ref name=\"Willamette-valley-railways\">{{cite book |last=Thompson |first=Richard |title=Willamette Valley Railways |date=January 1, 2008 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G42lB3U1aQUC&pg=PA29 |publisher=[[Arcadia Publishing]] |page=29 |isbn=978-0738556017}}</ref> The OE line's Tualatin depot is believed to have stood on the site of the present-day WES station.<ref name=\"proposed\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ci.tualatin.or.us/departments/communitydevelopment/planning/docs/CommuterRail/AR-07-03%20Narrative%20Info.pdf |title=Proposed Tualatin Commuter Rail Station and Park & Ride |date=January 25, 2007 |publisher=[[Tualatin, Oregon|City of Tualatin]] |access-date=October 13, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609144453/http://www.ci.tualatin.or.us/departments/communitydevelopment/planning/docs/CommuterRail/AR-07-03%20Narrative%20Info.pdf |archive-date=June 9, 2011}}</ref> As [[Car|automobile]] use increased in the 1920s, passenger volume on the line failed to grow as projected. This resulted in OE ending passenger rail service in May 1933. [[Diesel locomotive|Diesel]] [[Rail freight transport|freight]] service continued to run along the route into the 1990s.<ref name=\"Willamette-valley-railways\"/><ref name=\"wes-factsheet\">{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/publications/pdf/factsheets/wes.pdf |title=WES Commuter Rail |publisher=[[TriMet]] |date=July 2016 |access-date=February 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180509045301/http://trimet.org/publications/pdf/factsheets/wes.pdf |archive-date=May 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\nLed by Washington County officials, planning for a commuter rail line between Beaverton and Wilsonville began in 1996.<ref name=\"wes-factsheet\"/> Local governments authorized the project in 2001. After several years of delays owing to a lack of funding, the [[Federal Transit Administration]] approved the line's construction in 2004.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2004/05/10/daily9.html |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Wilsonville-to-Beaverton commuter train gets OK |publisher=[[Portland Business Journal]] |date=May 10, 2004 |access-date=August 20, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110525222054/http://www.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2004/05/10/daily9.html |archive-date=May 25, 2011}}</ref> Plans for a station in the city of Tualatin were finalized as early as 2001, when a site along Boones Ferry Road was selected in consideration of the city's transportation plan.<ref name=\"railstop\">{{cite news |last=Bella |first=Rick |title=Tualatin rail stop overrides differences |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |date=September 26, 2007 |page=C1}}</ref> Construction of the rail line began in October 2006.<ref name=conbegin>{{cite news |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2006/10/23/daily1.html |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=TriMet building passenger train line |publisher=Portland Business Journal |date=October 23, 2006 |access-date=August 20, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110525222103/http://www.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2006/10/23/daily1.html |archive-date=May 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, [[Haggen|Haggen Food & Pharmacy]], a grocery store situated next to the station's proposed location, embarked on efforts to have it moved. They contended the station did not have enough parking\u2014original plans included 111 parking spaces\u2014and increased traffic would worsen congestion around the area.<ref name=haggen>{{cite news |last=Tran |first=My-Thuan |title=Tualatin station short on parking, firm reports |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=March 20, 2007 |page=B3}}</ref><ref name=\"Tran, My-Thuan 2007\">{{cite news |last=Tran |first=My-Thuan |title=TriMet, Haggen to meet on moving Tualatin station |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=June 14, 2007 |page=D3}}</ref> Haggen's arguments led to a delay in the station's construction, which had been scheduled to begin in July 2007.<ref name=haggen/><ref>{{cite news |last=Tran |first=My-Thuan |title=West side onboard for risky rail ride |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=April 10, 2007 |page=B1}}</ref> The city and TriMet countered that the location had been selected in 2001 and re-affirmed in 2005 with no objections from Haggen. TriMet later threatened to forgo having a station in the city.<ref name=\"railstop\"/>\n\nIn August 2007, the two sides compromised. The station's location remained as planned but additional parking was added.<ref name=\"railstop\"/><ref name=\"ok\">{{cite news |last=Foyston |first=John |title=Businesses OK site for rail station in Tualatin |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=August 3, 2007 |page=D3}}</ref> On January 9, 2008, the station's construction began with a groundbreaking ceremony attended by local dignitaries.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Foyston |first1=John |last2=Mayes |first2=Steve |title=Construction will start on commuter station |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=January 8, 2008 |page=C3}}</ref> The public artwork was installed in September 2008.<ref>{{cite news |last=Foyston |first=John |title=Ambitious crews install 5 steel sculptures in a day |date=September 4, 2008 |newspaper=The Oregonian}}</ref> Tualatin station was completed in time for the line's opening on February 2, 2009.<ref name=\"oct1ann\">{{cite news |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/environment/index.ssf/2008/10/trimet_delays_opening_of_wests.html |first=Dylan |last=Rivera |title=TriMet delays opening of Westside commuter rail line until February |date=October 1, 2008 |newspaper=The Oregonian |access-date=October 2, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090617200611/http://www.oregonlive.com/environment/index.ssf/2008/10/trimet_delays_opening_of_wests.html |archive-date=June 17, 2009}}</ref><ref name=oreg-2009feb3>{{cite news |last=Crepeau |first=Megan |title=Westside commuter rail launch smooth<!--(print-edition headline)--> |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=February 3, 2009 <!--(online date Feb. 2)--> |page=B2 |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/washingtoncounty/index.ssf/2009/02/wes_debuts_smoothly_but_with_a.html |accessdate=August 15, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141019184648/http://www.oregonlive.com/washingtoncounty/index.ssf/2009/02/wes_debuts_smoothly_but_with_a.html |archive-date=October 19, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Station details==\n[[File:Tualatin-WES-station-March-2019.jpg|thumb|alt=Photograph of Tualatin Station showing the clock tower and red brick support columns with ornate light standards and a roadway in the foreground | The station seen from across Boones Ferry Road]]\n\n{|table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=3\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" width=60 rowspan=4 valign=top|'''Platform level'''\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px black;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 2px black;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|{{small|[[Side platform]], doors will open on the left or right}}\n|-\n|width=100| '''Northbound'''\n|width=420|<span style=\"color:white\">\u2192</span> '''[[WES Commuter Rail|WES]]''' toward [[Beaverton Transit Center]] <small>([[Tigard Transit Center]])</small> \u2192\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\"|'''Southbound'''\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\"| \u2190 '''[[WES Commuter Rail|WES]]''' toward {{stn|Wilsonville}} <small>(Terminus)</small>\n|}\n\nTualatin station is situated on the east end of Hedges Green Shopping Center near the intersection of [[Oregon Route 141|Southwest Boones Ferry Road]] and Southwest Seneca Street in downtown Tualatin.<ref name=\"even-six-months\">{{cite news |last=Clampet |first=Jennifer |url=http://www.tigardtimes.com/news/story.php?story_id=119992441787360700 |title=Even six months late, WES to arrive on time in Tualatin |newspaper=[[The Times (Tigard)|The Times]] |date=January 10, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717055226/http://www.tigardtimes.com/news/story.php?story_id=119992441787360700 |archive-date=July 17, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/ride/stop.html?stop_id=13069 |title=Stop ID 13069 \u2013 Tualatin WES Station |publisher=TriMet |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201185746/https://trimet.org/ride/stop.html?stop_id=13069 |archive-date=February 1, 2019 |access-date=February 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> It is one of five WES stops along the {{convert|14.7|mi|adj=on}} rail line owned by [[Portland and Western Railroad]].<ref name=\"ground\">{{cite news |last=Tucker |first=Libby |title=Commuter rail project breaks ground in Wilsonville |publisher=[[Daily Journal of Commerce]] |date=May 3, 2007}}</ref> The station has 129 [[park and ride]] spaces, 24 covered [[Bicycle parking rack|bike rack]] spots, and six [[Bicycle locker|bike locker]]s.<ref name=\"wes-main\">{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/wes/index.htm |title=WES Commuter Rail |publisher=TriMet |access-date=January 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131162954/https://trimet.org/wes/index.htm |archive-date=January 31, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Its shelter exhibits enhancements to TriMet's standard design practices; it includes a [[clock tower]] and red brick columns that are intended to blend the platform in with the neighborhood's existing architectural styles.<ref name=\"ok\"/> The Tualatin Development Commission contributed $491,000 for its construction.<ref name=\"even-six-months\"/> The platform measures {{convert|146|ft|m}} in length and {{convert|15|ft|m}} in width, covers about {{convert|2000|sqft|m2}}, and sits four feet above the ground.<ref name=\"proposed\"/> The station features card-only [[ticket vending machine]]s and a [[Passenger information system|digital information display]] showing WES and bus arrival information.<ref name=\"wes-main\"/>\n\n===Public art===\n\nThe station's public art consists of an interactive [[sculpture]] created by [[Frank Boyden (artist)|Frank Boyden]] and [[Brad Rude]]. Entitled ''The Interactivator'', it features bronze heads and a vehicle designed to represent the train and the variety of people who ride the line. The vehicle moves along a track and has an animal figure displayed in a scene atop the piece.<ref name=\"the-interactivators\">{{cite book |url=https://trimet.org/publicart/pdf/wes-guide.pdf |last=Priester |first=Mary |title=The Interactivators: Sculpture for TriMet WES Commuter Rail |publisher=TriMet |date=2009 |isbn=978-0-9666762-1-1 |access-date=June 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302172936/http://trimet.org/publicart/pdf/wes-guide.pdf |archive-date=March 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{rp|28}} Additionally, glass in the windbreak is etched with a [[willow]] pattern.<ref name=\"wes-art\">{{cite web |url=http://www.trimet.org/commuterrail/publicart.htm |title=Public Art on Commuter Rail |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080917231638/http://trimet.org/commuterrail/publicart.htm |archive-date=September 17, 2008 |publisher=TriMet |access-date=August 21, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Services===\n\nTualatin station is the second of five northbound stops on the [[WES Commuter Rail]] line after [[Wilsonville station]] and before [[Tigard Transit Center]]. The line runs between the cities of Beaverton, Tigard, Tualatin, and Wilsonville and offers a connection to the [[MAX Blue Line|Blue]] and [[MAX Red Line|Red]] lines of [[MAX Light Rail]] at [[Beaverton Transit Center]].<ref>{{cite map |url=https://trimet.org/schedules/pdf/wes.pdf |title=WES Commuter Rail |publisher=TriMet |access-date=June 10, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302141721/http://trimet.org/schedules/pdf/wes.pdf |archivedate=March 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> WES operates only on weekdays during the morning and evening commutes and trains arrive at the station every thirty minutes per direction.<ref name=\"wes-sched-nb\">{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/schedules/w/t1203_1.pdf |title=WES Commuter Rail, Weekday To Beaverton |publisher=TriMet |access-date=January 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610194500/https://trimet.org/schedules/w/t1203_1.pdf |archive-date=June 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"wes-sched-sb\">{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/schedules/w/t1203_0.pdf |title=WES Commuter Rail, Weekday to Wilsonville |publisher=TriMet |access-date=January 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610194532/https://trimet.org/schedules/w/t1203_0.pdf |archive-date=June 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The station is also near a [[bus stop]] for TriMet's 76\u2013Hall/Greenburg route.<ref name=\"wes-main\"/> Additionally, the city of Tualatin provides the [[Tualatin Shuttle]], a free shuttle bus service operated by [[Ride Connection]], to connect riders between Tualatin station and local employers. The service, which operates two routes in the north and south areas surrounding Southwest Tualatin\u2013Sherwood Road, coordinates with WES train arrivals and is free for use by the public.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tualatinoregon.gov/communitydevelopment/ride-connection |title=Ride Connection |publisher=[[Tualatin, Oregon|City of Tualatin]] |access-date=January 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131160929/https://www.tualatinoregon.gov/communitydevelopment/ride-connection |archive-date=January 31, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://rideconnection.org/assets/pdf/Tualatin_Shuttle_Brochure.pdf?c= |title=Tualatin Shuttle Brochure |publisher=Ride Connection |date=July 11, 2016 |access-date=January 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131162126/https://rideconnection.org/assets/pdf/Tualatin_Shuttle_Brochure.pdf?c= |archive-date=January 31, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Tualatin station}}\n{{Portal|Oregon|Trains}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/ride/stop.html?stop_id=13069 |title=Station information |publisher=[[TriMet]]}}\n\n{{TriMet railway stations|WES=y}}\n{{Tualatin, Oregon}}\n\n[[Category:2009 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Bus stations in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Washington County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in the United States opened in 2009]]\n[[Category:Transportation buildings and structures in Washington County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Tualatin, Oregon]]\n[[Category:WES Commuter Rail]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox Station\n | name           = {{MAX infobox header|Tualatin|wesstn=y}}\n | type           = [[WES Commuter Rail]] station\n | image          = Tualatin station platform view, showing gauntlet track (2015).jpg\n | image_caption  = Tualatin station seen in 2015\n | address        = 18955 Southwest Boones Ferry Road [[Tualatin, Oregon]], U.S.\n | country        = \n | line           = [[Portland and Western Railroad]]\n | coordinates    = {{coord|45.383283|-122.764556|format=dms|type:railwaystation_region:US-OR|display=inline,title}}\n | other          = \n | structure      = At-grade\n | platform       = 1 [[side platform]]\n | tracks         = 1\n | bus_operators  = \n | bus_routes     = \n | connections    = {{rint|bus|1}} '''TriMet''': 76{{br}}{{rint|bus|1}} '''Tualatin Shuttle'''\n | preceding      =\n | parking        = 129 spaces\n | bicycle        = [[Bicycle locker|Locker]]s and [[Bicycle parking rack|rack]]s\n | baggage_check  =\n | passengers     =\n | pass_year      =\n | pass_percent   =\n | pass_system    =\n | opened         = February 2, 2009\n | closed         =\n | rebuilt        =\n | ADA            = yes\n | code           =\n | owned          = [[TriMet]]\n | zone           =\n | services       = {{s-rail|title=WES}}\n{{s-line|system=WES|line=main|previous=Wilsonville|next=Tigard Transit Center}}\n | mpassengers=\n}}\n\n'''Tualatin ''' is a [[train station]] in [[Tualatin, Oregon]], United States. It is situated next to Hedges Green Shopping Center on [[Oregon Route 141|Southwest Boones Ferry Road]] in downtown Tualatin. The station is the second of five northbound stops on [[TriMet]]'s [[WES Commuter Rail]] after [[Wilsonville station]] and before [[Tigard Transit Center]]. The commuter rail line, which opened for regular service in February 2009, links the cities of [[Beaverton, Oregon|Beaverton]], [[Tigard, Oregon|Tigard]], Tualatin, and [[Wilsonville, Oregon|Wilsonville]] in the western suburbs of the [[Portland metropolitan area]]. WES connects with [[MAX Light Rail]] at [[Beaverton Transit Center]].\n\nThe station was approved as part of the [[Washington County, Oregon|Washington County]] commuter rail project in 2004. Construction was expected to begin in July 2007 but was delayed after issues emerged with its location, specifically the amount of available parking. A compromise was reached and construction began in January 2008. WES trains serve Tualatin station every thirty minutes on weekdays during the morning and evening [[rush hour]]s. Connections include TriMet bus route 76\u2013Hall/Greenburg and the [[Tualatin Shuttle]]. Tualatin station includes a 129-space [[park and ride]] lot.\n\n==History==\nBeginning in 1908, the [[Oregon Electric Railway]] (OE), which operated an [[interurban]] line between [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]] and [[Salem, Oregon|Salem]], served the community of Tualatin. At its peak, the line extended south as far as [[Eugene, Oregon|Eugene]].<ref name=\"Willamette-valley-railways\">{{cite book |last=Thompson |first=Richard |title=Willamette Valley Railways |date=January 1, 2008 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G42lB3U1aQUC&pg=PA29 |publisher=[[Arcadia Publishing]] |page=29 |isbn=978-0738556017}}</ref> The OE line's Tualatin depot is believed to have stood on the site of the present-day WES station.<ref name=\"proposed\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ci.tualatin.or.us/departments/communitydevelopment/planning/docs/CommuterRail/AR-07-03%20Narrative%20Info.pdf |title=Proposed Tualatin Commuter Rail Station and Park & Ride |date=January 25, 2007 |publisher=[[Tualatin, Oregon|City of Tualatin]] |access-date=October 13, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609144453/http://www.ci.tualatin.or.us/departments/communitydevelopment/planning/docs/CommuterRail/AR-07-03%20Narrative%20Info.pdf |archive-date=June 9, 2011}}</ref> As [[Car|automobile]] use increased in the 1920s, passenger volume on the line failed to grow as projected. This resulted in OE ending passenger rail service in May 1933. [[Diesel locomotive|Diesel]] [[Rail freight transport|freight]] service continued to run along the route into the 1990s.<ref name=\"Willamette-valley-railways\"/><ref name=\"wes-factsheet\">{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/publications/pdf/factsheets/wes.pdf |title=WES Commuter Rail |publisher=[[TriMet]] |date=July 2016 |access-date=February 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180509045301/http://trimet.org/publications/pdf/factsheets/wes.pdf |archive-date=May 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\nLed by Washington County officials, planning for a commuter rail line between Beaverton and Wilsonville began in 1996.<ref name=\"wes-factsheet\"/> Local governments authorized the project in 2001. After several years of delays owing to a lack of funding, the [[Federal Transit Administration]] approved the line's construction in 2004.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2004/05/10/daily9.html |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Wilsonville-to-Beaverton commuter train gets OK |publisher=[[Portland Business Journal]] |date=May 10, 2004 |access-date=August 20, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110525222054/http://www.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2004/05/10/daily9.html |archive-date=May 25, 2011}}</ref> Plans for a station in the city of Tualatin were finalized as early as 2001, when a site along Boones Ferry Road was selected in consideration of the city's transportation plan.<ref name=\"railstop\">{{cite news |last=Bella |first=Rick |title=Tualatin rail stop overrides differences |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |date=September 26, 2007 |page=C1}}</ref> Construction of the rail line began in October 2006.<ref name=conbegin>{{cite news |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2006/10/23/daily1.html |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=TriMet building passenger train line |publisher=Portland Business Journal |date=October 23, 2006 |access-date=August 20, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110525222103/http://www.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2006/10/23/daily1.html |archive-date=May 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, [[Haggen|Haggen Food & Pharmacy]], a grocery store situated next to the station's proposed location, embarked on efforts to have it moved. They contended the station did not have enough parking\u2014original plans included 111 parking spaces\u2014and increased traffic would worsen congestion around the area.<ref name=haggen>{{cite news |last=Tran |first=My-Thuan |title=Tualatin station short on parking, firm reports |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=March 20, 2007 |page=B3}}</ref><ref name=\"Tran, My-Thuan 2007\">{{cite news |last=Tran |first=My-Thuan |title=TriMet, Haggen to meet on moving Tualatin station |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=June 14, 2007 |page=D3}}</ref> Haggen's arguments led to a delay in the station's construction, which had been scheduled to begin in July 2007.<ref name=haggen/><ref>{{cite news |last=Tran |first=My-Thuan |title=West side onboard for risky rail ride |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=April 10, 2007 |page=B1}}</ref> The city and TriMet countered that the location had been selected in 2001 and re-affirmed in 2005 with no objections from Haggen. TriMet later threatened to forgo having a station in the city.<ref name=\"railstop\"/>\n\nIn August 2007, the two sides compromised. The station's location remained as planned but additional parking was added.<ref name=\"railstop\"/><ref name=\"ok\">{{cite news |last=Foyston |first=John |title=Businesses OK site for rail station in Tualatin |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=August 3, 2007 |page=D3}}</ref> On January 9, 2008, the station's construction began with a groundbreaking ceremony attended by local dignitaries.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Foyston |first1=John |last2=Mayes |first2=Steve |title=Construction will start on commuter station |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=January 8, 2008 |page=C3}}</ref> The public artwork was installed in September 2008.<ref>{{cite news |last=Foyston |first=John |title=Ambitious crews install 5 steel sculptures in a day |date=September 4, 2008 |newspaper=The Oregonian}}</ref> Tualatin station was completed in time for the line's opening on February 2, 2009.<ref name=\"oct1ann\">{{cite news |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/environment/index.ssf/2008/10/trimet_delays_opening_of_wests.html |first=Dylan |last=Rivera |title=TriMet delays opening of Westside commuter rail line until February |date=October 1, 2008 |newspaper=The Oregonian |access-date=October 2, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090617200611/http://www.oregonlive.com/environment/index.ssf/2008/10/trimet_delays_opening_of_wests.html |archive-date=June 17, 2009}}</ref><ref name=oreg-2009feb3>{{cite news |last=Crepeau |first=Megan |title=Westside commuter rail launch smooth<!--(print-edition headline)--> |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=February 3, 2009 <!--(online date Feb. 2)--> |page=B2 |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/washingtoncounty/index.ssf/2009/02/wes_debuts_smoothly_but_with_a.html |accessdate=August 15, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141019184648/http://www.oregonlive.com/washingtoncounty/index.ssf/2009/02/wes_debuts_smoothly_but_with_a.html |archive-date=October 19, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Station details==\n[[File:Tualatin-WES-station-March-2019.jpg|thumb|alt=Photograph of Tualatin Station showing the clock tower and red brick support columns with ornate light standards and a roadway in the foreground | The station seen from across Boones Ferry Road]]\n\n{|table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=3\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" width=60 rowspan=4 valign=top|'''Platform level'''\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px black;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 2px black;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|{{small|[[Side platform]], doors will open on the left or right}}\n|-\n|width=100| '''Northbound'''\n|width=420|<span style=\"color:white\">\u2192</span> '''[[WES Commuter Rail|WES]]''' toward [[Beaverton Transit Center]] <small>([[Tigard Transit Center]])</small> \u2192\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\"|'''Southbound'''\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\"| \u2190 '''[[WES Commuter Rail|WES]]''' toward {{stn|Wilsonville}} <small>(Terminus)</small>\n|}\n\nTualatin station is situated on the east end of Hedges Green Shopping Center near the intersection of [[Oregon Route 141|Southwest Boones Ferry Road]] and Southwest Seneca Street in downtown Tualatin.<ref name=\"even-six-months\">{{cite news |last=Clampet |first=Jennifer |url=http://www.tigardtimes.com/news/story.php?story_id=119992441787360700 |title=Even six months late, WES to arrive on time in Tualatin |newspaper=[[The Times (Tigard)|The Times]] |date=January 10, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717055226/http://www.tigardtimes.com/news/story.php?story_id=119992441787360700 |archive-date=July 17, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/ride/stop.html?stop_id=13069 |title=Stop ID 13069 \u2013 Tualatin WES Station |publisher=TriMet |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201185746/https://trimet.org/ride/stop.html?stop_id=13069 |archive-date=February 1, 2019 |access-date=February 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> It is one of five WES stops along the {{convert|14.7|mi|adj=on}} rail line owned by [[Portland and Western Railroad]].<ref name=\"ground\">{{cite news |last=Tucker |first=Libby |title=Commuter rail project breaks ground in Wilsonville |publisher=[[Daily Journal of Commerce]] |date=May 3, 2007}}</ref> The station has 129 [[park and ride]] spaces, 24 covered [[Bicycle parking rack|bike rack]] spots, and six [[Bicycle locker|bike locker]]s.<ref name=\"wes-main\">{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/wes/index.htm |title=WES Commuter Rail |publisher=TriMet |access-date=January 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131162954/https://trimet.org/wes/index.htm |archive-date=January 31, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Its shelter exhibits enhancements to TriMet's standard design practices; it includes a [[clock tower]] and red brick columns that are intended to blend the platform in with the neighborhood's existing architectural styles.<ref name=\"ok\"/> The Tualatin Development Commission contributed $491,000 for its construction.<ref name=\"even-six-months\"/> The platform measures {{convert|146|ft|m}} in length and {{convert|15|ft|m}} in width, covers about {{convert|2000|sqft|m2}}, and sits four feet above the ground.<ref name=\"proposed\"/> The station features card-only [[ticket vending machine]]s and a [[Passenger information system|digital information display]] showing WES and bus arrival information.<ref name=\"wes-main\"/>\n\n===Public art===\n\nThe station's public art consists of an interactive [[sculpture]] created by [[Frank Boyden (artist)|Frank Boyden]] and [[Brad Rude]]. Entitled ''The Interactivator'', it features bronze heads and a vehicle designed to represent the train and the variety of people who ride the line. The vehicle moves along a track and has an animal figure displayed in a scene atop the piece.<ref name=\"the-interactivators\">{{cite book |url=https://trimet.org/publicart/pdf/wes-guide.pdf |last=Priester |first=Mary |title=The Interactivators: Sculpture for TriMet WES Commuter Rail |publisher=TriMet |date=2009 |isbn=978-0-9666762-1-1 |access-date=June 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302172936/http://trimet.org/publicart/pdf/wes-guide.pdf |archive-date=March 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{rp|28}} Additionally, glass in the windbreak is etched with a [[willow]] pattern.<ref name=\"wes-art\">{{cite web |url=http://www.trimet.org/commuterrail/publicart.htm |title=Public Art on Commuter Rail |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080917231638/http://trimet.org/commuterrail/publicart.htm |archive-date=September 17, 2008 |publisher=TriMet |access-date=August 21, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Services===\n\nTualatin station is the second of five northbound stops on the [[WES Commuter Rail]] line after [[Wilsonville station]] and before [[Tigard Transit Center]]. The line runs between the cities of Beaverton, Tigard, Tualatin, and Wilsonville and offers a connection to the [[MAX Blue Line|Blue]] and [[MAX Red Line|Red]] lines of [[MAX Light Rail]] at [[Beaverton Transit Center]].<ref>{{cite map |url=https://trimet.org/schedules/pdf/wes.pdf |title=WES Commuter Rail |publisher=TriMet |access-date=June 10, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302141721/http://trimet.org/schedules/pdf/wes.pdf |archivedate=March 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> WES operates only on weekdays during the morning and evening commutes and trains arrive at the station every thirty minutes per direction.<ref name=\"wes-sched-nb\">{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/schedules/w/t1203_1.pdf |title=WES Commuter Rail, Weekday To Beaverton |publisher=TriMet |access-date=January 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610194500/https://trimet.org/schedules/w/t1203_1.pdf |archive-date=June 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"wes-sched-sb\">{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/schedules/w/t1203_0.pdf |title=WES Commuter Rail, Weekday to Wilsonville |publisher=TriMet |access-date=January 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610194532/https://trimet.org/schedules/w/t1203_0.pdf |archive-date=June 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The station is also near a [[bus stop]] for TriMet's 76\u2013Hall/Greenburg route.<ref name=\"wes-main\"/> Additionally, the city of Tualatin provides the [[Tualatin Shuttle]], a free shuttle bus service operated by [[Ride Connection]], to connect riders between Tualatin station and local employers. The service, which operates two routes in the north and south areas surrounding Southwest Tualatin\u2013Sherwood Road, coordinates with WES train arrivals and is free for use by the public.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tualatinoregon.gov/communitydevelopment/ride-connection |title=Ride Connection |publisher=[[Tualatin, Oregon|City of Tualatin]] |access-date=January 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131160929/https://www.tualatinoregon.gov/communitydevelopment/ride-connection |archive-date=January 31, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://rideconnection.org/assets/pdf/Tualatin_Shuttle_Brochure.pdf?c= |title=Tualatin Shuttle Brochure |publisher=Ride Connection |date=July 11, 2016 |access-date=January 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131162126/https://rideconnection.org/assets/pdf/Tualatin_Shuttle_Brochure.pdf?c= |archive-date=January 31, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Tualatin station}}\n{{Portal|Oregon|Trains}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/ride/stop.html?stop_id=13069 |title=Station information |publisher=[[TriMet]]}}\n\n{{TriMet railway stations|WES=y}}\n{{Tualatin, Oregon}}\n\n[[Category:2009 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Bus stations in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Washington County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in the United States opened in 2009]]\n[[Category:Transportation buildings and structures in Washington County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Tualatin, Oregon]]\n[[Category:WES Commuter Rail]]\n", "name_user": "Truflip99", "label": "safe", "comment": "abbr", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tualatin_station"}
